 MANAGEMENT OF INFORMATION SYSTEMS.DESCRIBES AND PRESENTS THE FINDINGS OF THE URBAN INFORMATION SYSTEMS (URBIS)PROJECT, CARRIED OUT IN 1973-78 BY THE URBIS RESEARCH GROUP OF THE PUBLICPOLICY RESEARCH ORGANIZATION, UNIVERSITY OF CALIFORNIA, IRVINE. THE PROJECT'SPURPOSE WAS TO ASSESS THE STATE-OF-THE-ART IN LOCAL GOVERNMENT COMPUTING,EVALUATE ITS IMPACT ON GOVERNMENT SERVICES AND MANAGEMENT DECISION-MAKING, ANDDEVELOP RECOMMENDATIONS FOR THE BETTER USE OF INFORMATION TECHNOLOGY.COMPUTING IN OVER 700 US CITIES AND COUNTIES WAS STUDIED EXTENSIVELY AND MOREDETAILED INFORMATION WAS THEN COLLECTED IN 42 CITIES. IT WAS FOUND THATWELL-MANAGED COMPUTER TECHNOLOGY HAS REAL PAY-OFFS, BUT THAT IT WAS NOTWELL-MANAGED IN MOST CITIES, CREATING PERVASIVE PROBLEMS AND PRODUCINGBENEFITS FAR SHORT OF EXPECTATIONS